      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἔπεμψα",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", in idiomatic English = “I have written,” but literally = “I did write”. If it were certain that the Epistle to the Colossians preceded that to the Ephesians, that the special mission on which Tychicus was sent with Onesimus to Colossæ took place before Paul wrote the Epistle to the Ephesians, and that he found some opportunity of forwarding the latter Epistle also in the course of Tychicus’s journey, the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἔπεμψα",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " would have its usual aorist sense, referring to a past act. Failing this, it must be taken as an instance of the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "epistolary",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " aor., the mission being ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "coincident",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " with the writing of the letter, but contemplated from the view-point of the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "recipients",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of the letter, to whom it was a thing of the past. The epistolary aor. certainly occurs in Latin, in the use of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "scripsi",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc. (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "cf.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Madvig, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Gr.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", § 345). How far its use extends in the NT is still a moot question, some finding many cases, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "e.g.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἔγραψα",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
